The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Bharti has an Ericsson edge
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Bharti has an Ericsson edge
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                          Expanding network                                  
	New Delhi, March 31: Bharti Airtel today signed a $1.3-billion network expansion contract with Swedens Ericsson.         
	The agreement will help Airtel to provide its users with enhanced voice quality, faster data access and more coverage in rural India.        
	Ericsson, the worlds biggest mobile network equipment maker, will also ensure that Bharti Airtels core and transport network is 3G-ready.        
	Airtel, which will bid for pan-India 3G spectrum on April 9, plans to roll out the high-speed services by the end of 2010.         
	We continue to be delighted with Ericssons expertise in network expansion and transformation, helping us reduce operating expenditure and enhance network quality. This way we can continue to provide a superior customer experience, said Sanjay Kapoor, CEO (India amp; South Asia), Bharti Airtel.         
	Ericsson will expand and upgrade Airtels network in 15 of Indias 22 telecom circles.         
	Hans Vestberg, president and CEO of Ericsson, said: Airtel is poised to spearhead the next telecom revolution in India and take the 2G experience to greater heights. In this partnership, we will set a new benchmark for the world in terms of network size and quality, types of services and end-user experience.        
	As part of this contract, Ericsson will supply its portfolio of 2G and 2.5G radio base stations, circuit and packet core, microwave transmission and intelligent network.         
	The expansion also covers the introduction of some of the latest technologies within the wireless world that will bring better voice quality to end users, support more users from one base station, ensure enhanced data rates using evolved EDGE technology and other new services.        
	Ericsson on Monday also signed two deals with Chinas top operators  a $1 billion deal with China Mobile and an $800 million contract with China Unicom.                                                                                                                                      
